frameDefinitions: The Agent is assigned to a Post where he or she performs a task associated with that Post.
An Employer employs an Employee whose Position entails that the Employee perform certain Tasks in exchange for Compensation.
An Employer hires an Employee, promising the Employee a certain Compensation in exchange for the performance of a job.
A Person is a member of an organized military organization belonging to a nation-state or similar body.
A Team is a group with shared goals and works toward them together in a coordinated fashion.
frameExamples: I <t>employed</t> him as Chief Gardener for ten years.
John was <t>hired</t> to clean up the file system.
The British at one point had an occupying army of over a million well-trained <t><fex name='Person'>soldiers</fex></t>.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Agent</fen> is assigned to a <fen>Post</fen> to perform a task involving a <fen>Salient_entity</fen>.
The <fen>Post</fen> is a location or station assigned to the <fen>Agent</fen> where a task or tasks are to be performed.
The <fen>Salient_entity</fen> is centrally involved in the task the <fen>Agent</fen> is assigned to perform. It is normally located at the <fen>Post</fen>.
This role identifies the time when the <fen>Agent</fen> works at the <fen>Post</fen>.
This role identifies the place where the <fen>Agent</fen> staffs the <fen>Post</fen>.
The role <fen>Employee</fen> denotes the person who is obligated to perform some <fen>Task</fen> in order to receive <fen>Compensation</fen>.
The <fen>Employer</fen> is the person (or institution) that gives <fen>Compensation</fen> to an <fen>Employee</fen>.
The role <fen>Field</fen> identifies the field in which the <fen>Employee</fen> is employed.
The role <fen>Position</fen> indicates a particular type of employment.
The <fen>Task</fen> indicates the action/duty that the <fen>Employee</fen> is obligated to do for the <fen>Employer</fen>.
The role <fen>Time</fen> identifies the time at whcih the <fen>Employer</fen> hires the <fen>Employee</fen>.
The role <fen>Place</fen> identifies the location where the <fen>Employer</fen> hires the <fen>Employee</fen>.
The person whom the <fen>Employer</fen> takes on as an <fen>Employee</fen>, obligating them to perform some <fen>Task</fen> in order to receive <fen>Compensation</fen>.
The person (or institution) that takes on an <fen>Employee</fen>, giving them  <fen>Compensation</fen> in return for the performance of an assigned <fen>Task</fen>.
The action that the <fen>Employee</fen> is taken on by the <fen>Employer</fen> to do.
The label given to a particular type of employment.
The <fen>Field</fen> that the <fen>Employee</fen> is going to work in for their <fen>Employer</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when an <fen>Employer</fen> hires the <fen>Employee</fen>.
This role identifies the place where the <fen>Employer</fen> hires the <fen>Employee</fen>.
The <fen>Person</fen> is the member of the military.
This role identifies the people or things that form  the <fen>Aggregate</fen>.
This role identifies the collection of entities that are the <fen>Team</fen>.
The job, obligation, or goal worked towards jointly by the <fen>Members</fen> of the <fen>Team</fen>.

Working the front desk <fex>at a real estate office</fex> is not as fulfilling as it might seem.
<fex>I</fex> was employed by an international corporation.
<fex>I</fex> employed him as Chief Gardener for ten years.
He was employed<fex>in finance</fex> fourteen years ago.
I am employed <fex>to collect the trash</fex>.
Charles has been an employee of Microsoft <fex>since 1998</fex>!
Actually, he employed me <fex> at the downtown office </fex>.
Last month, <fex>IBM</fex> hired Mike Zisman to head up its storage software group.
I was hired <fex>just to empty the trash cans</fex>.
Look, I wasn't hired <fex>as your waitress</fex>!
It's not easy to get hired <fex>in academia</fex>.
Actually, he hired me <fex>in a bordello</fex>.
